== Overview == According to the "{{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" ("Record of Ancient Matters"), the position of Kokuzō was established during the reign of Emperor {{ill|Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} when Hisatsuki no Atae, a descendant of the ancestor of the {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was appointed as Kokuzō. The "{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" also identifies {{ill|Ame-no-Hohi|ja|天之菩卑能命|1=Ame no Hohi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}’s child, {{ill|Takehiratori no Mikoto|ja|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|1=Takehi-Nateru|zh|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|fr|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, as the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō.<ref>The "Kojiki" notes that Takehiratori no Mikoto was the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō, among others, such as the {{ill|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|Izumo Province 造|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref>
This region boasted the {{ill|Kuriyama River|ja|栗山川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Tsubakimi Lake|ja|椿海|qq=draft|qq=draft}} water systems, yielding 80 dugout canoes—40% of Japan’s total excavated examples—and controlled waterways on the {{ill|Katori Sea|ja|香取海|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, suggesting its significant influence. Between the 4th and 5th centuries, prominent Kofuns such as {{ill|Shakushi Kofun|ja|しゃくし塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sannobunme Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|三ノ分目大塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were constructed.<ref>The use of {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|stone coffins|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in these tumuli indicates high-Ranking individuals.</ref><ref>Examples of Nagamochigata stone coffins, considered royal burials, are rare in the Kantō region.</ref> Along with {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko likely controlled an expansive area described as "Ō Unakami Kuni," stretching across modern Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, and Tokyo.
By the 6th century, the {{ill|Shiroyama No. 1 Kofun (Katori)|ja|城山1号墳 (香取市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Omaekizuka Kofun|ja|御前鬼塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were built, while the {{ill|Kinouchi Temple Ruins|ja|木内廃寺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} appeared during the transition from the Kokuzō system to the Ritsuryō system in the 7th century.
== Genealogy == The Kokuzō lineage includes the Hisatsuki family ({{ill|Kabane|ja|カバネ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}: {{ill|Atai|ja|直|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) and the Oda Hihafuri family (also titled Atai). Records indicate descendants served administrative roles and were acknowledged in later periods. Oda Hihafuri Shingō, noted in the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and Oda Hihafuri Tokutōji, mentioned in the {{ill|Man'yōshū|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, highlight their continued prominence.
Additionally, the Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō appears connected to {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as a clan deity, with the Oda Hihafuri family suspected as early ritual practitioners.<ref>Katori Shrine’s origins link to these clans.</ref>
== Related Sites == * {{ill|Raijin Shrine (Asahi City)|ja|雷神社 (旭市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== References == {{Reflist}}
== External Links == * [http://www.haniwakan.com/kenkyu/boso/simo.html Ancient Tumuli of Shimotsu Unakami Kuni]
