[[sn:Ukami kuni no miyatsuko]] [[ja:下海上国造]]
<!--Ukami kuni no miyatsuko-->

'''Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko''' (下海上国造, also known as Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō) governed the eastern portion of the later {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}} of {{ill|Shimōsa Province|ja|下総国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimōsa Province|qq=}}, covering present-day {{ill|Chōshi|ja|銚子市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōshi|qq=}}, {{ill|Asahi|ja|旭市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asahi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Katori District|ja|香取郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori District|qq=}} in {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}. The title is also written as 下菟上国造.
== Overview == According to the "{{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Kuji Hongi|qq=}}" ("Record of Ancient Matters"), the position of Kokuzō was established during the reign of Emperor {{ill|Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōjin|qq=}} when Hisatsuki no Atae, a descendant of the ancestor of the {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=}}, was appointed as Kokuzō. The "{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}" also identifies {{ill|Ame-no-Hohi|ja|天之菩卑能命|1=Ame no Hohi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Hohi|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame no Hohi|qq=}}’s child, {{ill|Takehiratori no Mikoto|ja|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|1=Takehi-Nateru|zh|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|fr|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehiratori no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehi-Nateru|qq=}}, as the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō.<ref>The "Kojiki" notes that Takehiratori no Mikoto was the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō, among others, such as the {{ill|Izumo clan|lt=Izumo clan|lt=Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|Izumo Province 造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}} and the {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Musashi Province|qq=}}.</ref>
This region boasted the {{ill|Kuriyama River|ja|栗山川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuriyama River|qq=}} and the {{ill|Tsubakimi Lake|ja|椿海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsubakimi Lake|qq=}} water systems, yielding 80 dugout canoes—40% of Japan’s total excavated examples—and controlled waterways on the {{ill|Katori Sea|ja|香取海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori Sea|qq=}}, suggesting its significant influence. Between the 4th and 5th centuries, prominent Kofuns such as {{ill|Shakushi Kofun|ja|しゃくし塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shakushi Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Sannobunme Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|三ノ分目大塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sannobunme Ōtsukayama Kofun|qq=}} were constructed.<ref>The use of {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniwa|qq=}} and {{ill|stone coffins|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone coffins|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} in these tumuli indicates high-Ranking individuals.</ref><ref>Examples of Nagamochigata stone coffins, considered royal burials, are rare in the Kantō region.</ref> Along with {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=}}, the Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko likely controlled an expansive area described as "Ō Unakami Kuni," stretching across modern Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, and Tokyo.
By the 6th century, the {{ill|Joyama Tomb No.1 (Katori)|lt=Joyama Tomb No.1 (Katori)|lt=Shiroyama No. 1 Kofun (Katori)|ja|城山1号墳 (香取市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiroyama No. 1 Kofun (Katori)|qq=}} and {{ill|Omaekizuka Kofun|ja|御前鬼塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Omaekizuka Kofun|qq=}} were built, while the {{ill|Kinouchi Temple Ruins|ja|木内廃寺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinouchi Temple Ruins|qq=}} appeared during the transition from the Kokuzō system to the Ritsuryō system in the 7th century.
== Genealogy == The Kokuzō lineage includes the Hisatsuki family ({{ill|Kabane|ja|カバネ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabane|qq=}}: {{ill|Atai|ja|直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Atai|qq=}}) and the Oda Hihafuri family (also titled Atai). Records indicate descendants served administrative roles and were acknowledged in later periods. Oda Hihafuri Shingō, noted in the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōsōin documents|qq=}}, and Oda Hihafuri Tokutōji, mentioned in the {{ill|Man'yōshū|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Man'yōshū|qq=}}, highlight their continued prominence.
Additionally, the Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō appears connected to {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori Shrine|qq=}} as a clan deity, with the Oda Hihafuri family suspected as early ritual practitioners.<ref>Katori Shrine’s origins link to these clans.</ref>
== Related Sites == * {{ill|Raijin Shrine (Asahi City)|ja|雷神社 (旭市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Raijin Shrine (Asahi City)|qq=}}
== References == {{Reflist}}
== External Links == * [http://www.haniwakan.com/kenkyu/boso/simo.html Ancient Tumuli of Shimotsu Unakami Kuni]
