[[sn:Ukami kuni no miyatsuko]] [[ja:下海上国造]]
<!--Ukami kuni no miyatsuko-->

'''Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko''' (下海上国造, also known as Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō) governed the eastern portion of the later [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] of [[:en:Shimōsa Province|Shimōsa Province]], covering present-day [[:en:Chōshi|Chōshi]], [[:en:Asahi, Chiba|Asahi]], and [[:en:Katori District|Katori District]] in [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]]. The title is also written as 下菟上国造.
== Overview == According to the "[[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]]" ("Record of Ancient Matters"), the position of Kokuzō was established during the reign of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Ōjin]] when Hisatsuki no Atae, a descendant of the ancestor of the {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=}}, was appointed as Kokuzō. The "[[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]" also identifies {{ill|Ame-no-Hohi|ja|天之菩卑能命|1=Ame no Hohi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Hohi|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame no Hohi|qq=}}’s child, {{ill|Takehiratori no Mikoto|ja|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|1=Takehi-Nateru|zh|建比良鳥命|1=Takehi-Nateru|fr|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehiratori no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehi-Nateru|qq=}}, as the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō.<ref>The "Kojiki" notes that Takehiratori no Mikoto was the ancestor of Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō, among others, such as the {{ill|Izumo clan|lt=Izumo clan|lt=Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|Izumo Province 造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}} and the {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Musashi Province|qq=}}.</ref>
This region boasted the [[:en:Kuriyama River|Kuriyama River]] and the {{ill|Tsubakimi Lake|ja|椿海|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsubakimi Lake|qq=}} water systems, yielding 80 dugout canoes—40% of Japan’s total excavated examples—and controlled waterways on the [[:en:Katori Sea|Katori Sea]], suggesting its significant influence. Between the 4th and 5th centuries, prominent Kofuns such as {{ill|Shakushi Kofun|ja|しゃくし塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shakushi Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Sannobunme Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|三ノ分目大塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sannobunme Ōtsukayama Kofun|qq=}} were constructed.<ref>The use of [[:en:Haniwa|Haniwa]] and {{ill|stone coffins|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone coffins|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} in these tumuli indicates high-Ranking individuals.</ref><ref>Examples of Nagamochigata stone coffins, considered royal burials, are rare in the Kantō region.</ref> Along with {{ill|Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|ja|上海上国造|1=Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiagami no Kuni Miyatsuko|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko|qq=}}, the Shimotsu Unakami no Kuni Miyatsuko likely controlled an expansive area described as "Ō Unakami Kuni," stretching across modern Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, and Tokyo.
By the 6th century, the {{ill|Joyama Tomb No.1 (Katori)|lt=Joyama Tomb No.1 (Katori)|lt=Shiroyama No. 1 Kofun (Katori)|ja|城山1号墳 (香取市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiroyama No. 1 Kofun (Katori)|qq=}} and {{ill|Omaekizuka Kofun|ja|御前鬼塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Omaekizuka Kofun|qq=}} were built, while the {{ill|Kinouchi Temple Ruins|ja|木内廃寺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinouchi Temple Ruins|qq=}} appeared during the transition from the Kokuzō system to the Ritsuryō system in the 7th century.
== Genealogy == The Kokuzō lineage includes the Hisatsuki family ([[:en:Kabane|Kabane]]: {{ill|Atai|ja|直|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Atai|qq=}}) and the Oda Hihafuri family (also titled Atai). Records indicate descendants served administrative roles and were acknowledged in later periods. Oda Hihafuri Shingō, noted in the {{ill|Shōsōin documents|ja|正倉院文書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōsōin documents|qq=}}, and Oda Hihafuri Tokutōji, mentioned in the [[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]], highlight their continued prominence.
Additionally, the Shimotsu Unakami Kokuzō appears connected to [[:en:Katori Shrine|Katori Shrine]] as a clan deity, with the Oda Hihafuri family suspected as early ritual practitioners.<ref>Katori Shrine’s origins link to these clans.</ref>
== Related Sites == * {{ill|Raijin Shrine (Asahi City)|ja|雷神社 (旭市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Raijin Shrine (Asahi City)|qq=}}
